snippet.textDisplay:
Sanders' opposition to means testing in non-universal government programming (like when he said he'd cancel the student debt of rich kids too) is literally the most radical policy stance in popular American politics today and that should say a lot. There's no need to create government programs designed with concessions to moderate politicians at every corner.
My family makes just enough money to not qualify for a lot of student financial aid but not enough money to actually pay off the debt piled onto us by the aid we do get. Every time there's means testing involved (like the Free Application for Federal Student Aid, that abomination of a document), there are thousands if not hundreds of thousands of families that are going to live within the valley that those concessions make and the government program loses its effectiveness for all those people.
THAT is why federal programs are failing: they're not serving everyone. They're serving just enough people to create good headlines and not enough people to squeak past opposition in the House and the Senate, and the republicans use that fact to defund and cut any government program they get their hands on.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have paid my student loans off and I loved this interview but one question Hasan asked that I'm getting very annoyed with hearing is: You, Bernie, are proposing canceling student loans debts. But what about all the people who just paid off their debts? Why is it being suggested that because folks have paid their debt off, it shouldn't be allowed to institute a great highly productive plan to stimulant the economy.
That's like saying Well Bernie shouldn't try a more peaceful approach with other nations. Bernie needs to keep up major on-going wars, since in the past other people's lives have been taken, so there for wars should continue. It's also like saying, Bernie shouldn't make corporations and millionaires pay their fair snare of taxes, because in the past I have had to pay more because corps haven't, therefore it's only fit allow things to continue as is." It's just a dumb question.
As I person who slowly has paid 90% off his $30K in student loan debt, I support Bernie's plan to wipe off student debt for others. I do not make much money, but still have no problems with other peoples debt being erased even though I tirelessly paid my off.
